==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ingredient
<hw>In*gre"di*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ingr⟦eacute⟧dient</ets>, L. <ets>ingrediens</ets>,
<ets>-entis</ets>, entering into, p. pr. of <ets>ingredi</ets>, p. p.
<ets>ingressus</ets>, to go into, to enter; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>gradi</ets> to walk, go. See <er>Grade</er>.]</ety> <def>That which
enters into a compound, or is a component part of any combination,
recipe, or mixture; an element; a constituent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By way of analysis we may proceed from compounds to
<qex>ingredients</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Water is the chief <qex>ingredient</qex> in all the animal fluids
and solids.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ingredient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ingredient
<hw>In*gre"di*ent</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Entering as, or forming, an
ingredient or component part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Acts where no sin is <qex>ingredient</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ingress</ent>⟦br⟧
